@NODE xyz "Hmm"

     @{b}GREAT!!@{ub}

Hmm... I think I'm above average programmer (aren't we all?;). I use mostly C in my Amiga programmes. Sometimes I also use AmigaE and Assembler (DevPac). I'm also quite good ARexx/CLI script writer. I love CygnusEd. I really hate GoldED. Hmm... What else? That's about it. :)

Oh, my Amiga's configuration?

Well, it's a good old A1200 put into 300W full tower case, 60 GB IDE hard disk, 40x IDE CD-ROM, HP CD-Writer+ 8100 CD-RW (with selfmade idefix hardware), 4.3 GB and 2.1 GB SCSI hard disks. Blizzard PPC Power Board equipped with 266 MHz 603e and 64.1 MHz 68060 (overclocking rules), and 32 MB + 64 MB 50ns SIMMs (total 96 MB fast), 10Mbit PCMCIA ethernet ($80 PC-card + PCMCIA reset hack), BlizzardVision PPC 8 MB graphics card (Permedia2 overclocked to 99MHz memclock), U.S.Blaster MM500 loudspeakers and finally HITACHI CM752ET 19" monitor. Quite ok system, no? :-)

Check http://www.iki.fi/sintonen/hw.html for updates. :)

And of course good old A500 (in 1001 pieces nowadays), few external drives and other stuff in my closet. ;)
@ENDNODE
@NODE Features "Features"

     @{b}FEATURES@{ub}

- @{"MuMove4K" LINK Modules} module, substitutes MuMove4K by Thomas Richter.

- CopyIDEfixPrefs and KingCON-handler.pch.

- QUICKBOOT feature as an external @{"QuickBoot" LINK Modules} module. Note that this module can probably only be used with Blizzard 1230s. You @{b}MUST@{ub} use LocalFast module too if you use this!

- Reintroduced LOCALFAST feature as an external @{"LocalFast" LINK Modules} module. Only use this module if you need to (mainly Blizzard 12x0s)! Also note that if you use LocalFast module you must start BlizKick before PoolMem.

- If PoolMem should cause troubles, doesn't crash anymore.

- Implemented EXTRESBUF more OS friendly way, fixes some problems

- New commandline argument: @{"SANITY" LINK Usage1}

- mmu.library support (not tested)

- Three new tools: @{"romupdatesplit" LINK Usage4}, @{"loadresident" LINK Usage5} and @{"protectextresbuf" LINK Usage8}.

- New section in guide about how to set up @{"AmigaOS 3.5/3.9 single boot system" LINK OS35setup}.

- You can give any executable as module! Renders SCSIDEV43 module obsolete (if using non-beta scsi.device!). Use V43 scsi.device, new fastfilesystem as a module and so on :)

- @{"applypatch" LINK Usage3} program to apply BlizKick patch kind of @{"modules" LINK Modules} to ROM image

- romfixes module to fix some @{"bugs" LINK rombugs} from rom

- AlertFix module to fix Blizzard PPC @{"`crash + reboot + alert' problem" LINK blizzppcfeatures} and other Alert related bugs.

- BPPCFix and BPPCFix040 modules to substitute BPPCFix by by Frank Wille <frank@phoenix.owl.de>

- ramlibstack module to substitute MCPRamlibPatch (also romfixes module has this functionality!)

- Support for Blizzard PPC

- Support for CPU Cards & CS MKI, MKII, MKIII and PPC!

- FusionReserve module to substitute RsrvCold tool of Fusion MAC Emulator (Also Mac1200), A1000Jingle to play some tune on reset, PatchMath020 to optimize C-compiler math routines in ROM, RebootFix to fix problems with A1200 and 060 (at least with BLIZZARD 1260) reboot when display is in multisync mode, and SpeedyChip module for patching 060 MMU lists for improved chip memory write speed.

- SCSIDEV43 module to kick V43 beta scsi.device. No more @{"4GB drive limit" LINK 4GBLimit}!

- Free100buf for freeing buffer created by ChipSaver module

- EXTRESBUF is put into fast memory now!

- ChipSaver, RemCards, SpeedyIDE and WaitIDE modules.

- NewAlert & BBlank modules by Jens Lorenz

- BKMODPATH env-variable can be used to specify location of BlizKick modules

- QUIET switch

- KICKFILE * can be used to kick original ROM found on chip

- BlizKick can replace SoftSCSI program!

- KICKFILE can be packed with XPK

- BlizKick can replace PrepareEmul 100%

- Can "expand" the ResidentTag area. No more "iffucient ROM space" -problem!

- Can be run any time (no more need to start before SetPatch on 1260)

- This package is free! (see @{"license" LINK License})

- Has possibility to plant ResidentTag @{"modules" LINK Modules} into ROM image!

- No kickstart file preparation or similar is needed. You can just save any ROM image and give it to BlizKick!

- Can restore the original Kickstart.

- Can make memory on Blizzard board LOCAL, bypass flashy boot of the board and speed up ROM boot.

- Has built-in FastWaitBlit patch.

- BlizKick is 100% assembler!

- BlizKick doesn't use MMU, KickMem, KickTag, ColdCapture or CoolCapture vectors. @{b}-> 100% transparent!@{ub}

- Works with almost any AmigaOS version! (that is AmigaOS 1.2 or better)

- BlizKick executable is only about 7K !

- BlizKick should be compatible with all future Kickstarts.

- Program for saving Kickstart ROM images included!
@ENDNODE
@NODE Requirements "Requirements"

     @{b}REQUIREMENTS@{ub}

BlizKick requires Amiga computer with AmigaOS 1.2 or better and phase5/DCE turbo board with its @{"MAPROM" LINK MAPROMJumper} feature enabled (or disabled for @{"some cards" LINK MAPROMJumper}!) or a CPU Card.

@{"SaveROM" LINK SaveROM} requires AmigaOS 1.0 or better.

Hard disk drive is highly recommended, but not required. You can also have problems reading this AmigaGuide document if you don't have MultiView because of \@WORDWRAP.

BlizKick should work with:

 ?  BLIZZARD 1230-I
 ?  BLIZZARD 1230-II
 x  BLIZZARD 1230-III
 x  BLIZZARD 1230-IV
 x  BLIZZARD 1240-T/ERC
 x  BLIZZARD 1260
 x  BLIZZARD 2040-ERC
 x  BLIZZARD 2060
 x  BLIZZARD Cyberstorm MKI
 x  BLIZZARD Cyberstorm MKII
 x  BLIZZARD Cyberstorm MKIII
 x  BLIZZARD Cyberstorm PPC
 x  BLIZZARD Blizzard PPC
 x  Commodore A3640

 x = tested and works
 ? = not tested, but should work
 - = not yet functional
 $ = might not work, I don't know if these boards have @{"MAPROM" LINK MAPROMJumper} feature
@ENDNODE
@NODE SaveROM "SaveROM utility"

     @{b}SAVEROM@{ub}

With this program you can save the current Kickstart ROM image into a kickfile. Kickfiles created with SaveROM can be @{"used" LINK Usage1} with BlizKick. See @{"usage" LINK Usage2} and @{"installation" LINK Installation} of the SaveROM.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Installation "BlizKick installation"

     @{b}INSTALLATION@{ub}


@{b}Just click @{"here" SYSTEM "Execute install_script"} to get BlizKick installed! (WILL COPY FILES AUTOMATICALLY! You still need to add BlizKick commandline to s:startup-sequence, see @{"BlizKick usage" LINK Usage1})@{ub}


If you simply want to get all programs and documentation installed automatically, click @{"here" SYSTEM "Execute install_script"}. Programs will be copied into C: -drawer, @{"Modules" LINK Modules} will be copied into DEVS:Modules -drawer, BKMODPATH env-variable is created and requester will pop up (OS 3.x) requesting destination directory for this AmigaGuide document. If you're OS 1.x/2.x user you should have HELP: -assign, as this document is copied into HELP:English or HELP: -drawer.

If you want to save your current Kickstart ROM into a file (DEVS:rom_@{fg shine}ver@{fg text}.@{fg shine}rev@{fg text}), click @{"here" SYSTEM "SaveROM DEVS:rom_v$kickstart"}. This kickfile can be used with BlizKick, it is the same version as already used, though :)

If you'll use @{"ChipSaver" LINK Modules} module you probably want to copy Free100buf to C: -drawer or drag it into WBStartup -drawer (You only should put Free100buf into WBStartup if you start ripper software before Workbench is loaded). You may @{" Copy Free100buf TO C: " SYSTEM "Copy FROM Free100buf TO C:"} and/or @{" Copy Free100buf Free100buf.info TO SYS:WBStartup/ " SYSTEM "Copy FROM Free100buf Free100buf.info TO SYS:WBStartup/"}.

Now, see @{"usage" LINK Usage1} section.

If you're interested in programming "@{"modules" LINK Modules}" or "@{"patches" LINK Modules}" see notes @{"here" LINK PrgNotes}.


     @{b}DETAILED INSTALLATION@{ub}
  (For you who hate automatic installation scripts)

BlizKick's installation is quite simple: just copy executable named @{b}BlizKick@{ub} into your C: -drawer. You also need @{"ROM image(s)" LINK KickImage} you want to rekick. If you're really lazy just hit the following button:

  @{" Copy BlizKick TO C:BlizKick " SYSTEM "Copy FROM BlizKick TO C:BlizKick"}

There is also a program for saving (grabbing) Kickstart ROMs included (@{"SaveROM" LINK SaveROM}). If you want, you can copy it into your C: -drawer by clicking the following button:

  @{" Copy SaveROM TO C:SaveROM " SYSTEM "Copy FROM SaveROM TO C:SaveROM"}

If you want to "prepatch" ROM image with patch kind of @{"modules" LINK Modules} install @{"applypatch" LINK Usage3} by clicking the button below:

  @{" Copy applypatch TO C:applypatch " SYSTEM "Copy FROM applypatch TO C:applypatch"}

If you want to split AmigaOS 3.5/3.9 ROM Update file install @{"romupdatesplit" LINK Usage4} by clicking the button below:

  @{" Copy romupdatesplit TO C:romupdatesplit " SYSTEM "Copy FROM romupdatesplit TO C:romupdatesplit"}

If you want to add resident modules to EXTRES buffer after BlizKick has been run install @{"loadresident" LINK Usage5} by clicking the button below:

  @{" Copy loadresident TO C:loadresident " SYSTEM "Copy FROM loadresident TO C:loadresident"}

If you want to MMU protect resident modules in EXTRES buffer, install @{"protectextresbuf" LINK Usage8} by clicking the button below:

  @{" Copy protectextresbuf TO C:protectextresbuf" SYSTEM "Copy FROM protectextresbuf TO C:protectextresbuf"}

If you want to use new IDEfix as a module CopyIDEfixPrefs can be used to update the IDEfixPrefs to C:IDEfix file. Install @{"CopyIDEfixPrefs" LINK Usage6} by clicking the button below:

  @{" Copy CopyIDEfixPrefs TO C:CopyIDEfixPrefs " SYSTEM "Copy FROM CopyIDEfixPrefs TO C:CopyIDEfixPrefs"}

There are some example @{"modules" LINK Modules} included. If you want, you can copy them into your DEVS: -drawer by clicking the following button:

  @{" Copy Modules/~(#?.(ASM|i)) DEVS:Modules " SYSTEM "Copy >NIL: Modules/~(#?.(ASM|i)) DEVS:Modules"}

Finally you could add a environment variable BKMODPATH which contains path for BlizKick modules (default "DEVS:Modules/").

Of course, you should copy (drag?) this AmigaGuide documentation into your Docs-drawer.

See usage of @{"BlizKick" LINK Usage1}, @{"SaveROM" LINK Usage2} and @{"applypatch" LINK Usage3}.


     @{b}UNINSTALLATION@{ub}

Delete C:BlizKick, C:SaveROM, C:applypatch, C:romupdatesplit, C:loadresident, C:protectextresbuf and C:CopyIDEfixPrefs, delete DEVS:Modules ALL, delete ENVARC:BKMODPATH and delete this guide file.
(Above is valid for default installation)
If you have copied Free100buf to C: and/or SYS:WBStartup/ -drawer(s) you should delete it too.
@ENDNODE
@NODE PrgNotes "Programmer's notes"

     @{b}PROGRAMMER'S NOTES@{ub}

You should copy file Modules/@{"blizkickmodule.i" LINK Modules/blizkickmodule.i/main} into your @{b}include:@{ub} -drawer.

There are assembler source code for all included modules! These files aren't copied by installation process. You might want to create Modules drawer to place where this guide file is located and copy all .ASM files into it.

Then see @{"example modules" LINK ExampleModules}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE doub! "How it is done?"

     @{b}HOW IT IS DONE?@{ub}

Certain phase5/DCE turbo boards have @{"MAPROM" LINK MAPROMJumper} feature, which can be used to load (copy) currently installed ROM chip into the 32-bit fast memory. I found that the memory for the Kickstart ROM is "allocated" from the end of the memory installed on board. Because the memory isn't actually allocated, but the AddMemList() function parameters are changed a bit, the memory area containing the ROM is outside the system memory pool.

What I do in BlizKick is really quite simple: I test whether system has somewhat valid phase5/DCE turbo board installed and its MAPROM feature enabled. If all is OK so far, I allocate memory for the specified @{"Kickstart ROM" LINK KickImage} kickfile and load it. The I Disable() system and run some piece of code in CPU's supervisor state. It effectivily does nothing exceptional: It just copies the loaded ROM over the Kickstart ROM created by boards own "MAPROM" and flushes CPU caches. Finally, execbase is trashed and reset is done.

Wow! Isn't that simple!
@ENDNODE
@NODE Notes "Important notes"

     @{b}NOTES@{ub}

MorphOS loader takes over whole system memory overwriting everything, including EXTRES area. So EXTRESBUF can't be used if you're going to use MorphOS. Also be sure you use qstartup/startup Kickstart option, and do NOT use applypatched ROM Image here, but the original ROM! MorphOS @{b}will@{ub} misbehave if it can't apply its' own patches!

If you have Blizzard PPC read @{"Blizzard PPC special" LINK blizzppcspecial} notes.

It might be that RemCards module can't be used if you have CD-ROM drive. This depends on the drive controller/device driver.

If you want to use SCSIDEV43 module with SpeedyIDE and/or WaitIDE module then SpeedyIDE and/or WaitIDE must be specified after SCSIDEV43 or else it won't work (as patches are made to ROM scsi.device which is immeditially replaced by V43 scsi.device).

As of version 1.11ß1 EXTRESBUF is put into board's own fast memory, not chip memory.

If you want to use NoClick module with Hackdisk module then NoClick must be specified after Hackdisk or else drives will continue clicking. I've also found that hackdisk.device has some problems in conjugation with CrossDos6. If you have any problems, just don't use hackdisk module.

Kickstart 1.2 (33.180) works now, as BlizKick automagically patches some bugs of it.

Please, see @{"why" LINK Others} you show use BlizKick 1.24 instead of other similar programs.

If you're interested in programming "@{"modules" LINK Modules}" or "@{"patches" LINK Modules}" for BlizKick see notes @{"here" LINK PrgNotes}.

There's a @{"certain bug" LINK BlizBug} in at least 1230-II and 1230-III boards: memory node name can sometimes be a null string.

You can save (grab) the modified ROM created by BlizKick. It can be used with other "kicking" tools with no problems (at least if EXTRESBUF feature isn't used). Using it with BlizKick again requires use of the FORCE switch. See @{"usage" LINK Usage1} of the BlizKick.

BlizKick can be used in conjugation with Enforcer, CPU FASTROM, VMM, GigaMem etc. BTW: BlizKick has few Enforcer hits, but they'll never show up as Enforcer is turned off when needed... :) I'm well aware that no program should access memory areas outside of memory lists, but this is a @{"hack" LINK doub!} anyway...

Note that you should @{b}not@{ub} use Kickstart 1.3 or lower on systems equipped with MC68040 or better processor. This doesn't mean you can't do it though... :)

BlizKick has been tested on following systems:

  A1200, BLIZZARD 1230-I 68EC030 @ 40MHz
  A1200, BLIZZARD 1230-III 68030 @ 50MHz
  A1200, BLIZZARD 1230-IV 68030 @ 50MHz
  A1200, BLIZZARD 1240-T/ERC 68040 @ 40MHz
  A1200, BLIZZARD 1260 68060 @ 50MHz
  A1200, BLIZZARD 1260 68060 @ 50MHz
  A1200, Blizzard PPC 603e+ @ 270Mhz, 68060 @ 64.1MHz
  A?000, BLIZZARD 2040-ERC 68040 @ 40MHz
  A2000, BLIZZARD 2060 68060 @ 50MHz
  A4000, Cyberstorm MK II 68060 @ 50MHz
  A4000, Cyberstorm MK III 68060 @ 50MHz
  A4000, Cyberstorm PPC 604e @ 200MHz, 68060 @ 50MHz

  (+ many other configurations)

BlizKick should work with all @{"phase5/DCE turbo boards" LINK Requirements} that have @{"MAPROM" LINK MAPROMJumper} feature enabled. If you're having troubles with BlizKick on your system and you're sure that your board is Blizzard board and it has MAPROM feature, then contact @{"me" LINK About}. I'll fix BlizKick, if possible. I cannot guarantine BlizKick to be 100% software/hardware compatible!

You @{b}must@{ub} have the @{"MAPROM" LINK MAPROMJumper} feature enabled or BlizKick won't work!

Note that BlizKick uses always 512K of memory, even if the ROM image to rekick is only 256K (KS 1.x). This is because of phase5/DCE turbo's own MAPROM feature and can't be fixed (easily). The memory area before 256K ROM ($F80000-$FBFFFF) contains the same data as at $FC0000 (this is what happens with real 256K ROM too).

You can use modified ROM images as BlizKick always resums the image before it's kicked. Naturally you should be careful when changing ROM contents, but simple funny things like string modifications etc. should be easy thing to do. Of course, you should always have backup of the original ROM kickfile!

BlizKick doesn't use kickmem or kicktag vectors, or Cold- or CoolCapture.

BlizKick should be compatible with all future Kickstarts and Kickstart images. There is one restriction though: 1MB ROM images can't be used. Again, this is because of phase5/DCE turbo's MAPROM feature. KS 1.2, 1.3, 2.04, 2.05, 3.0 and 3.1 are currently tested ROM images. If BlizKick refuses to co-operate with other ROM images (256K/512K) then contact @{"me" LINK About}.

If you rekick older kickstart than originally used one, it may be impossible to use all hardware and/or peripherals of your system (e.g. If you originally use KS 3.0 in your A1200 and rekick KS 1.3 you can't use your hard disk drives or PCMCIA slot. Direct banging of AGA hardware works, if someone is smart (?) enough to do it).

Here is some @{"information" LINK Disclaimer} about different Kickstart ROM images:

KS		SIZE VERS	NOTES

1.0		ĽMB 30.x	Used in old AMIGA 1000
1.1 ntsc		ĽMB 31.x	Used in AMIGA 1000
1.1 pal		ĽMB 32.x	Used in AMIGA 1000
1.2		ĽMB 33.x	Original A500 ROM
1.3		ĽMB 34.x	Can run AUTOBOOT devices
1.4		??MB 35.x	KS 1.3 with A2410 support
2.0,2.01,2.02	˝MB 36.x	Beta OS 2.0
2.04 		˝MB 37.175	Official OS 2.0
2.05		˝MB 37.300	Used in A600's, knows how to
				use internal AMIGA 600/AMIGA
				1200/AMIGA 4000 IDE
				peripherals and PCMCIA slot.
				Doesn't work with Bliz 1260!
3.0		˝MB 39.106	Official OS 3.0
3.0beta		˝MB 39.107	Beta?
3.0beta		˝MB 39.110	Beta?
3.1		˝MB 40.x	Support for Akiko and CD-ROM
3.2		˝MB 43.x	Would have been used in
				"Walker"...?
@ENDNODE
@NODE BlizBug "Bug in BLIZZARD 1230-II and 1230-III"

     @{b}BLIZZARD BOARD BUG@{ub}

There's a little bug in Blizzard boards autoconfig(TM) code (at least 1230-II and 1230-III):

When the board allocates memory for the memory node name of the boards' memory it can sometimes fail.

There's a code like this:

	move.l	(.stringsize,pc),d0
	moveq	#MEMF_ANY,d1
	movea.l	(4).w,a6
	jsr	(_LVOAllocMem,a6)
	movea.l	d0,a3		@{b}movea.l <ea>,An WON'T set@{ub}
	beq.b	.nomem		@{b}condition codes! -> fail!@{ub}
	movea.l	a3,a1
	lea	(.blizmem,pc),a0
.copy	move.b	(a0)+,(a1)+
	bne.b	.copy
.nomem
	movea.l	a3,a1
	;...
	; add memory to system memory pool
	; a1=ptr to memory node name
	;...

.stringsize	dc.l	20
.blizmem	dc.b	'Blizzard_Mem',0

@{bg shine}@{b} THIS IS TOTALLY WRONG! @{ub}@{bg back}

@{b}1]@{ub} movea.l <ea>,an does @{b}not@{ub} set condition codes like move <ea>,<ea> does! This code can think allocation failed when it succeeded, and think it succeeded when it really failed (!).

@{b}1)@{ub} Should movea.l d0,a3, tst.l d0, beq.b .nomem

@{b}1>@{ub} Now if there's no memory, Blizzard memory node won't have any name which is perfectly legal.
@ENDNODE
@NODE 040060Notes "Attention, 68040/68060 user!"

     @{b}68040/68060 NOTES@{ub}

You need @{b}not@{ub} start BlizKick before SetPatch. See @{"why" LINK Because}. 
From version 1.6 and on you can start BlizKick anytime!

I've received some reports that BlizKick 1.9 wouldn't have worked if run after SetPatch on 68040 or 68060 systems. It this still happens please contact @{"me" LINK About}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Because "SetPatch and 68040/68060"

     @{b}SETPATCH AND 68040/68060@{ub}

When SetPatch is run, it'll load 680x0.library. 680x0.library will set up MMU tables so that it'll hide magic MAPROM memory areas from all other programs.

To get around this BlizKick will toggle MMU on and off couple of times while it's run. Note that BlizKick won't change MMU tables in any way, or turn MMU off if it was initially on.
@ENDNODE
@NODE blizzppcspecial "Blizzard PPC special"

     @{b}BLIZZARD PPC SPECIAL@{ub}

From version 1.19 on, BlizKick is cabable of starting more than once per poweron (use @{"FORCE" LINK Usage1})! You can also restore the original ROM (give no @{"KICKFILE" LINK Usage1}). I finally managed to find the way to disable the Blizzard PPC maprom... :)

@ENDNODE
@NODE ffs62fuckup "ffs62 module fuckup"

     @{b}STORY OF FFS62 MODULE@{ub}

  Background story:

Once I was examining ffs partition with diskmontools and found out that there seemed to be "empty" space after file/dir name in file/dir block. So after hours of resourcing I was able to locate all places in which fastfilesystem handles file/dir names (hashing routines etc). Then I wrote patch to modify these places, and wow: I had fastfilesystem with max. 62 char filesnames. Well, I really thought so, but it was too good to be true... :-(

  What went wrong then?

Well I accidently included this beta module to BlizKick 1.13 Aminet release. It wasn't supposed to get included but my automatic aminet packaging script was a bit too efficient.

Then later I was talking with Ralph Schmidt and he told me that this ffs62 patch overwrites some fields in file/dir block. Ooops, bad luck! I still don't know 100% what these fields are but apparently this ffs62 just seemed to work for me (by luck).

  Conlusion:

see @{"disclaimer" LINK Disclaimer}. ;-)
@ENDNODE

@NODE TroubleShoot "Troubleshooting"

     @{b}TROUBLESHOOTING@{ub}


@{b}IMPORTANT:@{ub} If your problem isn't covered here it might be a good idea to look at http://www.iki.fi/sintonen/sw.html for the latest BlizKick beta release (topmost BlizKick in the table). It could be that the bug has been fixed already!

@{b}Q: romfixes module print errors! It appears to work nevertheless.

A: Since the 1.24rc3 release, romfixes module no longer fail completely, but print "warning" messages of patches it cannot apply. Those messages are harmless and can be ignored.

@{b}Q: I use scsi.device 43.35+ and SCSIDEV43 module doesn't seem to work anymore! My system only see scsi.device 40.x.@{ub}

A: AmigaOS 3.5 and 3.9 scsi.device should be used as a module. Copy scsi.device into your modules dir and use "scsi.device" as a module.

@{b}Q: I added the new MuMove4K module and removed PrepareEmul/FusionReserve module. Now ShapeShifter/Fusion don't work anymore!@{ub}

A: Don't remove PrepareEmul/FusionReserve module, it's still needed. (Michael D)

@{b}Q: When BlizKick has loaded it reboots the system, and then my system give me red screen (ROM checksum error). If I give my machine three-finger-salute (Ctrl-Amiga-Amiga) and afterwards it works just fine, and the ROM is mapped ok. What's up?@{ub}

A: I finally managed to trace the root of this problem! It seems that the reboot magic in some PowerUP boards is somehow broken, and cause this "one-shot ROM checksum error". I could avoid this problem by replacing the official PowerUP reboot code with standard one. You can choose this new reboot method with @{"NOPUPREBOOT option" LINK Usage1} (new in BlizKick 1.24beta8).

@{b}Q: I have a JST installed game X that doesn't work anymore!@{ub}

A: Try removing SpeedyIDE module, it might help. (Jacob Jensen)

@{b}Q: AmigaOS 3.5/3.9 romupdate console.device doesn't work as module!@{ub}

A: Pre-1.6 romfixes module didn't like OS 3.5/3.5 console.device. romfixes 1.6 silently skip the console.device patching if V44+ console.device is around.

@{b}Q: I put BlizKick to my s:startup-sequence and now it keeps on rebooting my machine over and over again!@{ub}

A: This can happen if you have used some other tool to map the ROM before BlizKick is run. Make sure you've disabled the other tools (incl. CS PPC/MKIII's maprom from bootmenu!), then power off, and turn your Amiga back on. It should work then (just one reboot). (Thanks to Gunther Nikl for this one.)

@{b}Q: Rafal Mania's InitPPCLib 1.1 doesn't work with BPPFix 1.2 module!?@{ub}

A: Yep. At least the 'os-friendly version' doesn't. But hey you can always use 'BPPCFixFix' or 'loadppclib' written by me... :-)

@{b}Q: I am running UAE on my amiga and I don't use rom-file. If I am using EXTRESBUF with BlizKick, UAE fail to start. Why?@{ub}

A: UAE cannot find the EXTRES buffer memory and fail miserably. However this is easy to fix; just use rom-file with UAE.

@{b}Q: With my A4000 + A3640 BlizKick work when started from shell when system has booted. However it fails when I put it to startup-sequence. Why?@{ub}

A: It seems that with A3640 you need to place the BlizKick command after SetPatch line. If someone has ideas how to make it work before SetPatch let me know.

@{b}Q: muFastZero FASTEXEC doesn't work with BlizKick?@{ub}

A: Seems so. Use BlizKick's LocalFast module instead. (Thanks to Matt for this one.)

@{b}Q: When I use BlizKick and start MorphOS my system just freezes. Even if it did work I can't get back to AmigaOS without powering down. Why?@{ub}

A: MorphOS loader takes over whole system memory overwriting everything, including EXTRES area. So EXTRESBUF can't be used if you're going to use MorphOS. Also be sure you use qstartup/startup Kickstart option, and do NOT use applypatched ROM Image here, but the original ROM! MorphOS @{b}will@{ub} misbehave if it can't apply its' own patches!

@{b}Q: I have AlertFix module installed and every app doing exec/Alert() gives me error instead of alert.@{ub}

A: AlertFix-module V1.0 was broken and caused this problem as a side effect. 1.22beta12 added new fixed 1.1 version of AlertFix. (a fix on a fix :-)

@{b}Q: KingCON-module doesn't werk, you sux!@{ub}

A: It doesn't work with AmigaOS 3.5/3.9. Too bad. The patch was written by Mikolaj Calusinski so I'm afraid I can't help much. On the other hand, who need KingCON in ROM anyway? :-)

@{b}Q: BlizKick seems to work properly on the 1st boot. On the next reboot I get red screen and/or system hangs/infinite reboots.@{ub}

A: Four possibilities:

a) If you have a SCSI-kit or BlizzardPPC and only one SIMM module installed you might want to try swapping the slot the module is in or try adding 2nd SIMM. This could help. (thanks for the tip CISC!)
b) Some program is trashing the MAPROM area. Try to find and remove such program, use enforcer kind of tool to find the offending software.
c) Your card's MAPROM is defective (I know at least one case).
d) BlizKick has a bug (again:). If it doesn't seem to be neither a), b) nor c) please let @{"me" LINK About} know.
e) Did I say four? Oh well it can be some stupid mistake or weird hardware problem. Wave a chicken over it, might help...

@{b}Q: BlizKick seems to reboot the system twice!? I am using AmigaOS 3.5/3.9.@{ub}

A: BlizKick doesn't reboot the system 2nd time, it's the SetPatch installing "devs:AmigaOS ROM Update" -file. However, the 2nd boot can be avoided. Read how to set up @{"AmigaOS 3.5/3.9 single boot system" LINK OS35setup}.

@{b}Q: This new LocalFast module doesn't work! The old BlizKick that had it built in worked!@{ub}

A: Due silly mistake external LocalFast module didn't work before 1.22beta4. I'm truly sorry. :)

@{b}Q: BlizKick seems to do its job properly but then it fails my startup-sequence with failure code 20. What's up?@{ub}

A: Most probably bug in BlizKick. You might be still able to use BlizKick though, just add 'failat 21' command before BlizKick. Also please report this behaviour to @{"me" LINK About}.

@{b}Q: I added QuickBoot module to my setup and it fails/hangs/crashes my system!@{ub}

A: QuickBoot probably only works with Blizzard 1230-II and III. Possibly also 1230-IV, 1240 and 1260.

A: You must use LocalFast module with QuickBoot, it won't work without.

@{b}Q: I have ramlibstack and romfixes modules on BlizKick commandline and BlizKick just fails with returncode 10. Why?@{ub}

A: romfixes module includes ramlibstack module functionality. Remove ramlibstack module from commandline.

@{b}Q: When I use romupdatesplit to split "devs:AmigaOS ROM Update" -file I don't get the modules shown in @{"romupdatesplit example" LINK Usage4}! (FileSystem.resource file is missing!) Why?@{ub}

A: That example run is done with AmigaOS 3.5 BoingBag2a service pack installed. And that list shows the module output on a A1200 machine. You should update to BoingBag2a anyhow, it contains lots of bug fixes!

@{b}Q: BlizKick 1.19 and 1.20 didn't work at all!@{ub}

A: There was a major bug in copymem routine for 68040 and 68060 CPUs. Fixed in 1.21.

@{b}Q: I get weird crash and/or alert 80010000! What can I do?@{ub}

A: BlizKick 1.20+ can probably help here, use new @{"SANITY option" LINK Usage1}.

@{b}Q: I have a module called ffs62 what is supposed to give me max 62 character filenames for FFS. It seems to work, but should I really use it?@{ub}

A: @{b}DON'T USE IT!@{ub} It @{"never worked" LINK ffs62fuckup}.

@{b}Q: BlizKick seems to be unable to find any modules without paths! I have `assign ENV: RAM:' line before BlizKick line.@{ub} (Thanks to Max for pointing this one out :)

A: BlizKick 1.19 and later will find modules in this case too, previous releases had problems with this.

@{b}Q: BlizKick doesn't work with my Blizzard PPC!@{ub}

A: It does work, read @{"Blizzard PPC special" LINK blizzppcspecial}.

@{b}Q: BlizKick doesn't work for me.@{ub}

A: Don't turn on every feature, you know what happened in Tshernobyl... Try it as 'BlizKick *', if that doesn't work then BlizKick is a bit broken (probably). You could try contacting @{"me" LINK About}, I might even be able to fix it. Don't expect miracles though.

@{b}Q: FusionReserve module doesn't work!@{ub}

A: It does work. Get FixPATCHMAC.lha from aminet and use it conjugation with FusionReserve module.

@{b}Q: PrepareEmul and FusionReserve modules don't work together!@{ub}

A: FusionReserve substitutes PrepareEmul in this case. If you use FusionReserve module you don't need to use MoveVBR module either as FusionReserve moves VBR by itself too.

@{b}Q: My CD-ROM drive refuses to work when I use BlizKick!@{ub}

A: Don't use RemCards module. If you still have problems then contact @{"me" LINK About}.

@{b}Q: When I use BlizKick and start Linux my system just freezes. Even if it did work I can't get back to AmigaOS without powering down. Why?@{ub}

A: Linux loader takes over whole system memory overwriting everything, including EXTRES area. So EXTRESBUF can't be used if you're about to boot Linux.

@{b}Q: WaitIDE doesn't work on V43.17 scsi.device!@{ub}

A: It didn't work in 1.11ß3. WaitIDE should work with it as of 1.11ß4. V43.17 IDE device recognization is broken. :(

@{b}Q: I use SCSIDEV43 module but I only get boot-hand picture. What's wrong?@{ub}

A: Well some releases of V43 scsi.device are broken. At least V43.17 doesn't work for me. V43.11 and V43.18 work.

@{b}Q: SpeedyIDE and/or WaitIDE don't seem to work when used with SCSIDEV43 module. Why?@{ub}

A: You must always specify SpeedyIDE and WaitIDE modules after SCSIDEV43.

@{b}Q: SpeedyIDE causes checksum errors (or other failures) on my hard disk(s)!?@{ub}

A: It works on my A1200, I see no reason why it should't work on your system too. If any problems arise, please disable SpeedyIDE and let DiskSalv or similar program fix your hard disk(s). See also @{"disclaimer" LINK Disclaimer} :).

@{b}Q: I install hackdisk module, but my system freezes immeditially after I've installed disk. I have CrossDos6 or newer. What's wrong?@{ub}

A: I've found that hackdisk.device has some problems in conjugation with CrossDos v6+. If you have any problems, just don't use hackdisk module. I can't fix this yet because I really don't have a clue what's wrong with hackdisk... :(

A: I've heard that original author of Hackdisk, Dan Babcock, is about to release V3.0 of Hackdisk soon. That version is supposed to fix all current problems (I hope so! :).

@{b}Q: When I use hackdisk module ARTM (for example) shows that there's no hackdisk.device resident tag installed! Why?@{ub}

A: This is normal! If hackdisk module initializes without errors it should be there! It is supposed to look like trackdisk.device because it's a full trackdisk replacement (It is even copied over trackdisk.device in ROM!). There's a HackDiskTest program included in NewHackdisk distribution (disk/misc/NewHackdisk.lha) which will display hackdisk version string (and return RC as 0) if it's installed. You can also use other tools (for example DiskMon) to see if hackdisk is really there...

@{b}Q: BlicKick doesn't work! I have memory only on SCSI-Kit.@{ub}

A: MAPROM requires memory on turbo board itself. Solution to this would be to purchase 2, 4 or 8 MB SIMM to be installed into boards SIMM slot. Problems may arise if you have, for example overclocked 68060 to 66MHz and the fan covers SIMM socket (partially).

@{b}Q: NoClick doesn't work when used with hackdisk module!@{ub}

A: Try specifying NoClick module after hackdisk. It should work then.

@{b}Q: When I use BlizKick with EXTRESBUF ShowConfig will report something like this:
        Node type $A, Attributes $703 (CHIP), at $1E000020-$1FFFFF (~3618.0 meg)@{ub}

A: ShowConfig is bad. This is not my fault. @{b}NOTE:@{ub} EXTRESBUF doesn't magically add chip memory... :)

@{b}Q: If I already have latest ROM in my machine how can I use for example EXTRESBUF without romfile?@{ub}

A: Use * as KICKFILE. 512K of ram is lost (as usual) though.

@{b}Q: EXTRESBUF fails on 1240/2040/2060!? System locks up!@{ub}

A: Hmmm... It should work. Please inform @{"me" LINK About}!

@{b}Q: SoftSCSI does not work.@{ub}

A: It didn't work in 1.9ß5, but should work now. Be sure to have DEVS:Modules/A1234.ROM file present!

@{b}Q: Kickstart 1.2 doesn't seem to work! I get only a yellow screen etc... What's up?@{ub}

A: As of version 1.10ß3 Kickstart 1.2 (33.180) should work! BlizKick automagically patches some bugs of it.

@{b}Q: I know that BlizKick 1.10 on BLIZZARD 1260 can be started after SetPatch, but is the any difference starting it before or after? Which should I prefer?@{ub}

A: No, there shouldn't be any difference. If you use BlizKick just to change (update) your Kickstart (for example 3.0 to 3.1), then you should insert line running BlizKick as first command in your s:startup-sequence. You can - of course - start BlizKick later on too, but I'll then take more time to boot up at the first time...

A: I've received some reports that BlizKick 1.9 wouldn't have worked if run after SetPatch on 68040 or 68060 systems. It this still happens please contact @{"me" LINK About}.

@{b}Q: Help! BlizKick doesn't work!?@{ub}

A: You need @{"phase5/DCE turbo board" LINK Requirements} with its @{"MAPROM" LINK MAPROMJumper} feature enabled.

@{b}Q: Why should I use BlizKick? BlizzMagic looks fine to me...@{ub}

A: OK! OK! Use BlizzMagic if you like... But then you'll of course miss some nice features only present in BlizKick, like external @{"modules" LINK Modules}... @{"See" LINK Other1} why I prefer BlizKick. It's up to you.

A: To see comparisations between BlizKick and other similar programs, see @{"here" LINK Others}.

@{b}Q: IDE devices of my AMIGA 600/AMIGA 1200/AMIGA 4000 don't work when I use KS 1.x or 2.04. Why?@{ub}

A: If you rekick older kickstart than originally used one, it may be impossible to use all hardware and/or peripherals of your system (e.g. If you originally use KS 3.0 in your A1200 and rekick KS 1.3 you can't use your hard disk drives or PCMCIA slot). Kickstart 2.05 (37.300) should be able to use IDE controller of the AMIGA 600/AMIGA 1200/AMIGA 4000. Sadly it seems as 2.05 wouldn't work on BLIZZARD 1260... ;-(

@{b}Q: My 68040/68060 system crashes when I try to use KS 1.x! This is definitely BlizKick's fault!?@{ub}

A: No. KS 1.x @{b}won't@{ub} work properly with 68040/68060.

A: Actually, you might be able to use it... :)

@{b}Q: I took kickfile from XYZKicker and it doesn't work with BlizKick! Why?@{ub}

A: Hmm... Probably "XYZKicker" has specially tuned ROM images (relocated to $200000? ;-( ) Kickfiles used with BlizKick mustn't be (de)relocated or tempered with. To get 100% working kickfile, use @{"SaveROM" LINK SaveROM} program to grab it from ROM chip.

@{b}Q: BlizKick sucks!?@{ub}

A: No. BlizKick is great.

@{b}Q: I try to use kickfile for KS 40.70, but it fails! Why?@{ub}

A: Be sure you don't have A4000 version as it doesn't work on A1200. A1200 version of KS 40.70 should work, although it isn't tested.

@{b}Q: I use kickfile for KS 40.68, but it can't use any external Modules! Why?@{ub}

A: Kickstart 40.68 doesn't have enough @{"free ROM space" LINK Planting} in it. ;-( Well, this is not a problem anymore with BlizKick 1.6 and on: Just use @{"EXTRESBUF" LINK Usage1} feature!

@{b}Q: Oh-no!! BlizKick failed saying "object too large, Couldn't plant module 'xxx'!" Help!!@{ub}

A: There's no more space for external Modules, so you must use @{"EXTRESBUF" LINK Usage1} feature or increase the buffer size if it's already in use.

@{b}Q: BlizKick failed saying "object wrong type, Couldn't plant module 'xxx'!" !! What's up!?@{ub}

A: You tried to use non-module file as @{"module" LINK Modules} or the module isn't supported by this BlizKick version.

@{b}Q: HOGWAITBLIT don't work with KS 1.x!?@{ub}

A: Right. Nothing can be done about this.

@{b}Q: Why are you releasing this great package as freeware? I'd ask money for it!@{ub}

A: Sorry, I like it free. ;-)

@{b}Q: When I kick 256K ROM 512K of memory is lost! Why?@{ub}

A: @{"MAPROM" LINK MAPROMJumper} feature of the phase5/DCE boards normally take 512K. It @{b}could@{ub} be possible to patch ROM in such way it would add those unused 256K back to system memory pool, but since it's only 256K I won't bother. And hey: who uses KS 1.x anyway!?

@{b}Q: I have a phase5/DCE board and memory on it, but when I examine my system's memory node list, there's no node with name 'Blizzard_Mem' (or similar). Why?@{ub}

A: There's a @{"bug" LINK BlizBug} in at least 1230-II and 1230-III boards: memory node name can sometimes be a null string.

A: On BLIZZARD 1260 memory node name pointer is always null (which is, btw, 100% legal!).

@{b}Q: When I tried to kick ROM, my machine just hangs! Keyboard reset doesn't help either. Why?@{ub}

A: You @{b}might@{ub} have used trashed/bad kickstart ROM. You have to turn power off and on again. If you have BlizKick installed into your startup-sequence and your machine hangs again and again you have to break booting and remove (comment) line running BlizKick.

A: I have received a report that at least BlizKick release 1.5b caused a hang when used in conjugation with 1230-IV and SCSI-Kit. If you're sure you have 100% working ROM (it works on your friends machine for example), but BlizKick hangs on your system, you should send me a detailed @{"bug report" LINK BugReports}. If this terrible thing should happen you could also try some @{"other" LINK Others} similar programs available... (NOT! :)

A: There are also different Kickstart ROM versions for different Amiga models (A500, A2000, A3000 should work with A1200 too). A4000 tuned ROMs may not work on A1200. Sorry, but I really don't know for sure! :(

@{b}Q: I have program called FastExec installed in my s:startup-sequence. Should it be before or after BlizKick?@{ub}

A: If you need FastExec, it should be after BlizKick.
@ENDNODE
