@NODE Usage8 "protectextresbuf: MMU protect EXTRES buffer"

     @{b}USAGE@{ub}

protectextresbuf's template is

  @{b}WRITEPROTECT/T, QUIET/S@{ub}

  @{b}WRITEPROTECT/T@{ub}
		Change EXTRES buffer write protect status.
		ON, YES: Turn writeprotect on.
		OFF, NO: Turn writeprotect off.

		@{b}NOTE:@{ub} If you use loadresident 1.0.2
		or better, you don't need to disable writeprotect
		if you want to load modules to EXTRES buffer.

  @{b}QUIET/S@{ub}
		Suppress program output.


Sample run:

  > protectextresbuf WRITEPROTECT ON
  protectextresbuf 1.0.1 by Harry "Piru" Sintonen
  EXTRES buffer is write enabled, change to write protected.

Another sample run:

  > protectextresbuf
  protectextresbuf 1.0.1 by Harry "Piru" Sintonen
  EXTRES buffer is write protected.


@{b}NOTES@{ub}

protectextresbuf support both Phase5/DCE 680x0.library and Thor's mmu.library. protectextresbuf should be started after SetPatch. The best solution is to add 'protectextresbuf >nil: writeprotect on', as this will suppress output even if BlizKick is not active.

Not all modules are ROMable. ROMable modules don't write EXTRES buffer by themselves. All modules provided by BlizKick itself are ROMable.

AmigaOS 3.5 and 3.9 ROM Update modules are ROMable.

3rd party modules might not be ROMable, for example IDEFix and KingCON-handler are @{b}NOT@{ub}, it will cause write hits if used in EXTRESBUF and EXTRESBUF is write protected.

protectextresbuf does not install any exception handler. If some application cause write hit to EXTRESBUF, the app will crash, unless Enforcer/Cyberguard/MuForce tool is running. Generally it is a good idea to run Cyberguard or MuForce.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Usage7 "make KingCON resident installable: KingCON-handler.pch"

     @{b}USAGE@{ub}

To be able to use l:KingCON-handler as external module it needs to be patched before. You need KingCON-handler 1.3, 020+ for this to work:

spatch -ot:KingCON-module -pKingCON-handler.pch l:KingCON-handler

If you get no error message and file t:KingCON-module exists spatch worked. Now you can copy t:KingCON-module to your module dir and add KingCON-module to BlizKick commandline.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Usage6 "copy new IDEFix prefs file to IDEfix executable: CopyIDEfixPrefs"

     @{b}USAGE@{ub}

This program is used to update the new IDEFix prefs file to IDEfix executable. This is needed if you use c:IDEfix as external module.

Sample run:

  > IDEfixPrefs

Change the preferences with the prefs editor. Save changes.

  > CopyIDEfixPrefs

This copies the modified preferences to c:IDEfix. You also *must* restart BlizKick, new setting won't take effect before.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Usage5 "Load resident tags to EXTRES buffer: loadresident"

     @{b}USAGE@{ub}

loadresident's template is

  @{b}MODULES/M, REBOOT/S@{ub}

  @{b}MODULES/M@{ub}
		Here you give list of all modules to load.
		You can NOT give BlizKick modules here!
		You can give scsi.device, FastFileSystem etc.
		If omit all resident tags inside EXTRES buffer
		are listed.

  @{b}REBOOT/S@{ub}
		After installing all modules succesfully,
		reboot after 1 second delay.


Sample run:

  > loadresident devs:modules/romupdate.idtag
  loadresident 1.0.3 by Harry "Piru" Sintonen
  Loading resident module devs:modules/romupdate.idtag... ok

Another sample run:

  > loadresident
  loadresident 1.0.3 by Harry "Piru" Sintonen

  EXTRESBUF at $6BD4E050 - $6BD6681F [MMU align at $6BD4E000 - $6BD67FFF, WRITE PROTECTED]
  Free: 18920 bytes  Largest: 18880 bytes
  Resident tags:

  $6BD4E050: EXTRES Handler
  $6BD4E170: FusionReserveVBR
  $6BD4E240: alert.hook
  $6BD4E590: console 44.6 (31.3.2000)
  $6BD52492: ram 44.21 (2.9.2000)
  $6BD548B0: filesysres 45.7 (17.9.2000)
  $6BD54A7E: fs 45.9 (3.9.2000)
  $6BD5B0C0: BPPCFix 1.2 (2.9.00)
  $6BD5B158: devprocfix.patchcode
  $6BD5B228: shellppc 50.8 (21.5.02) © 2001-2002 by Harry Sintonen, written by Harry Sint
  $6BD5F5DC: shellcmdppc 50.6 (17.5.02) © 2001-2002 by Harry Sintonen, written by Harry S


ps. Similarities with RemAPollo's loadresident are purely coincidental. :-)
@ENDNODE
@NODE Usage4 "AmigaOS 3.5/3.9 support: romupdatesplit"

     @{b}USAGE@{ub}

romupdatesplit's template is

  @{b}FROM=FILE/A, A600/S, A1200/S, A3000/S, A4000I/S,
  A4000S/S, CD32/S, CPU/K/N, FPU/K/N, NOBOARDCHECK/S,
  NOCOMMENT/S, ALL/S, TO@{ub}

  @{b}FROM=FILE/A@{ub}
		Here you specify full path of the AmigaOS 3.5/
		3.9 rom update file. It is installed to
		`DEVS:AmigaOS ROM Update' by default.

  @{b}A600/S@{ub}
		Extract Amiga 600 compatible module set. (Hardly
		useful but included for completeness;)

  @{b}A1200/S@{ub}
		Extract Amiga 1200 compatible module set.

  @{b}A3000/S@{ub}
		Extract Amiga 3000 compatible module set.

  @{b}A4000I/S@{ub}
		Extract Amiga 4000 IDE compatible module set.

  @{b}A4000S/S@{ub}
		Extract Amiga 4000[T] IDE *and* NCR scsi
		compatible module set.

  @{b}CD32/S@{ub}
		Extract CD32 specific module set.

  @{b}CPU/K/N@{ub}
		Specify CPU for CPU tagged modules.
		Can be 68000, 68010, 68020, 68030, 68040,
		68060.

  @{b}FPU/K/N@{ub}
		Specify FPU for FPU tagged modules.
		Can be 68881, 68882, 68040, 68060.

  @{b}NOBOARDCHECK/S@{ub}
		Extract all manufacturer / productid tagged
		modules.

  @{b}NOCOMMENT/S@{ub}
		By default romupdatesplit generates romtag
		idstring comments for generated files. This
		switch turns comment creation off.

  @{b}ALL/S@{ub}
		Get ALL modules from file.

  @{b}TO@{ub}
		Destination directory for resident tags
		written. Current directory by default.


@{b}NOTE:@{ub} If you don't specify any of the machine, cpu, fpu, noboardcheck or all switches romupdatesplit will extract modules the same way SetPatch does. This is usually what you want, as this is the module set compatible for your configuration.


Sample run:

  > romupdatesplit "devs:AmigaOS ROM Update" to t:
  00: flags $0000  offset $00003C  len $0000BC  "romupdate.idtag"
  01: flags $0000  offset $000108  len $0066C0  "FastFileSystem"
  02: flags $0000  offset $0067D8  len $0001E8  "FileSystem.resource"
  03: flags $0100  offset $0069D0  len $003B18  "scsi.device"
  08: flags $0000  offset $018FDC  len $002498  "ram-handler"
  09: flags $0000  offset $01B484  len $003F50  "console.device"

  *1  *2           *3              *4           *5

1: number of the executable the romupdate file
2: requirement flags for this resident tag, intentionally not
   documented here.
3: offset to beginning of executable file in the romupdate file
4: lenght of the executable file in the romupdate file
5: filename of the executable written. romupdatesplit tries its
   best on guessing this name.


This sample run was done with ROMUpdate 44.26 (2000-09-17) from AmigaOS 3.5 BoingBag2a. For A1200 it contains:

romupdate.idtag     - version tag for SetPatch
FastFileSystem      - fastfilesystem 45.9, same file is in l: ;)
FileSystem.resource - filesystem.resource 45.7
scsi.device         - A1200 IDE scsi.device 43.35
ram-handler         - ram-handler 44.21
console.device      - console.device 44.6

Personally I use FastFileSystem, FileSystem.resource, scsi.device, ram-handler and console.device as modules.

Read more about how to set up @{"AmigaOS 3.5/3.9 single boot system" LINK OS35setup}.

ps. Similarities with RemAPollo's RUX are purely coincidental. I coded romupdatesplit without knowing about RemAPollo... :-)
@ENDNODE
@NODE OS35setup "AmigaOS 3.5/3.9 single boot system"

     @{b}AMIGAOS 3.5/3.9 SINGLE BOOT SYSTEM@{ub}

AmigaOS 3.5/3.9 has updates for both Kickstart 3.1 and Workbench 3.1. SetPatch reads kickstart updates from "DEVS:AmigaOS ROM Update" -file and Workbench updates from libs:workbench.library and libs:icon.library files.

Kickstart updates require system reboot when installed. Workbench updates do not require boot.

It is possible to set up a BlizKick + AmigaOS 3.5/3.9 system that reboots only once at system power on. This is how it goes:

 - Use @{"romupdatesplit" LINK Usage4} program to extract AmigaOS 3.5/3.9 rom update modules:
   > romupdatesplit "devs:AmigaOS ROM Update" to devs:modules/
   00: flags $0000  offset $00003C  len $0000BC  "romupdate.idtag"
   01: flags $0000  offset $000108  len $0066C0  "FastFileSystem"
   02: flags $0000  offset $0067D8  len $0001E8  "FileSystem.resource"
   03: flags $0100  offset $0069D0  len $003B18  "scsi.device"
   08: flags $0000  offset $018FDC  len $002498  "ram-handler"
   09: flags $0000  offset $01B484  len $003F50  "console.device"

   (NOTE: the module output depends on "devs:AmigaOS ROM Update" version and your system configuration! This is just an example!)

 - Rename "devs:AmigaOS ROM Update" -file to something else or use NOROMUPDATE option with SetPatch (this prevents SetPatch from loading it)

 - Add EXTRESBUF=80000 and "FastFileSystem FileSystem.resource scsi.device ram-handler console.device" to MODULE line on BlizKick commandline:

   c:BlizKick [...] EXTRESBUF=80000 MODULE [...] FastFileSystem FileSystem.resource scsi.device ram-handler console.device [...]

 - You may want to add SpeedyIDE module after scsi.device to speed it up:

   c:BlizKick [...] EXTRESBUF=80000 MODULE [...] FastFileSystem FileSystem.resource scsi.device SpeedyIDE ram-handler console.device [...]

 - That's it!
@ENDNODE
@NODE Usage3 "How do I use applypatch?"

     @{b}USAGE@{ub}

applypatch's template is

  @{b}FROM=KICKFILE/A, TO/K/A, MODULE/M, FORCE/S, SPEEDROM/S,
  IGNPATH=IGNOREBKMODPATH/S, HOGWAITBLIT/S@{ub}

  @{b}FROM=KICKFILE/A@{ub}
		Here you specify full path of the source ROM
		image to apply patches to. Note that applypatch
		requires 512K ROM image. This argument is
		always required.

  @{b}TO/K/A@{ub}
		This argument specifies the full path of the
		destination ROM image to write. Note that you
                should not overwrite the source ROM image,
                always keep bakcups! This argument is always
                required.

  @{b}MODULE/M@{ub}
		Here you can give "patch" kind of @{"modules" LINK Modules} to
		apply to source ROM image. Multiple modules
		are allowed. BKMODPATH variable is supported.
		See @{"BlizKick usage" LINK Usage1} for more information.

		IMPORTANT! Not all modules can be given to
		applypatch! There is no easy way of knowing which
		modules work and which don't. However at least
		fixmath404, hogwaitblit, noclick, patchmath020,
		romfixes, speedrom, speedyide and waitide modules
		work.

  @{b}FORCE/S@{ub}
		If this switch is specified applypatch will use
		this ROM image, even if it has bad kickstart
		ROM checksum. This is switch is also needed if
		you're about to use grabbed ROM that has been
		previously used with BlizKick.

  @{b}SPEEDROM/S@{ub}
		This feature will speed up ROM. It will
		remove/disable some not so important parts of
		the ROM to gain some speed.

  @{b}HOGWAITBLIT/S@{ub}
		If you have an AGA chipset you use this switch
		to patch graphics.library/WaitBlit() to turn
		@{"BLITHOG" LINK BLITHOG} on during blit wait. This does almost
		the same thing as @{"FastWaitBlit" LINK FastWaitBlit} by Dave Jones,
		but is even @{"faster" LINK GfxBenchmarks}.
		HOGWAITBLIT requires V39 or better ROM image.

  @{b}IGNPATH=IGNOREBKMODPATH/S@{ub}
		If this switch is present MODULE option load
		the modules relative to current directory. Also
		BKMODPATH environment variable is not used then.

Sample run says it all:

  > applypatch DEVS:rom40068.A1200 TO T:rom40068.A1200.patched HOGWAITBLIT SPEEDROM NoClick FixMath404 SpeedyIDE PatchMath020 romfixes
  reading kickfile "DEVS:rom40068.A1200"...
  rom image ok, applying patches...
  applying hogwaitblit patch...
  applying NoClick patch...
  applying FixMath404 patch...
  applying SpeedyIDE patch...
  applying PatchMath020 patch...
  Patched DiceC Mulu routine at offset $27748
  applying romfixes patch...
  applying speedrom patch...

  ---- total 7 patches applied ----
  calculating new checksum for image... $04E754B7
  writing patched rom image to "T:rom40068.A1200.patched"...
  done.

Obviously you then copy this patched ROM image on harddisk and use it with BlizKick also removing patches already applied from BlizKick commandline.

@{b}NOTE:@{ub} If you intend to use SCSIDEV43 module with SpeedyIDE patched ROM image and you want the SpeedyIDE to take effect then you need to specify SpeedyIDE module again! (Otherwise scsi.device loaded by SCSIDEV43 module would overwrite the SpeedyIDE patched ROM scsi.device.)

Take this example:

C:BlizKick DEVS:rom40068.A1200.patched EXTRESBUF=16384 MODULE FusionReserve @{u}SCSIDEV43 SpeedyIDE@{uu} AlertFix QUIET
@ENDNODE

@NODE Usage1 "How do I use BlizKick?"

     @{b}USAGE@{ub}

BlizKick's template is

  @{b}KICKFILE, MODULE/M, EXTRESBUF/N, SANITY/K/N, FORCE/S,
  (LOCALFAST/S), (QUICKBOOT/S), SPEEDROM/S, HOGWAITBLIT/S,
  CPUCARD/S, IGNPATH=IGNOREBKMODPATH/S, NOPUPREBOOT/S,
  KEEPEXEC/S, QUIET/S@{ub}

  @{b}KICKFILE@{ub}
                Here you specify full path of the ROM image
		you want to kick.
		e.g. BlizKick KICKFILE="DEVS:rom image 3.1"

		If you don't specify kickfile and you've used
		BlizKick previously, original Kickstart will
		be restored.

		By specifying * as kickfile BlizKick will use
		the original ROM found on chip.

  @{b}MODULE/M@{ub}
		You can expand and patch your KS ROM by
		using "@{"Modules" LINK Modules}". From BlizKick 1.5 on it
		has been  possible to @{"plant" LINK Planting} external
		"@{"modules" LINK Modules}" into ROM image. Multiple modules
		are allowed. If you've @{"installed" LINK Installation} BlizKick,
		modules should reside on 'DEVS:Modules'
		-drawer. MODULE option will try to load the
		modules from DEVS:Modules by default:

	e.g. BlizKick DEVS:rom3.1 MODULE ColourModule romfixes

		Note that you can override the default directory
		with absolute path:

	e.g. BlizKick DEVS:rom3.1 MODULE work:blizkick/modules/romfixes

		As of version 1.10ß4 there can be a
		environment variable called BKMODPATH which
		holds path of BlizKick modules. This is handy
		if you for some reason keep the modules in some
		other directory. For example:

	> setenv BKMODPATH work:blizkick/modules/
	> copy env:BKMODPATH envarc:

		Now BlizKick MODULE default path is
		"work:blizkick/modules/".

		@{b}NEW in 1.20:@{ub} You can give @{b}any@{ub} executable
		file as module! Naturally this executable should
		contain valid resident tag or else it doesn't do
		anything. This feature renders SCSIDEV43 module
		obsolete (if using non-beta scsi.device!), you can
		give scsi.device as a module, also you can update
		ROM filesystem by just giving l:fastfilesystem as a
		module!

		As of 1.22beta6 two new support tools were added:
		@{"CopyIDEfixPrefs" LINK Usage6} and @{"KingCON-handler.pch" LINK Usage7}. With
	 	these it is possible to use c:IDEfix and
		l:KingCON-handler as modules!

		@{"romupdatesplit" LINK Usage4} tool can be used to
		extract resident tags from AmigaOS 3.5/3.9
		`DEVS:AmigaOS ROM Update' file.

		See how to set up @{"AmigaOS 3.5/3.9 single boot system" LINK OS35setup}.

		@{"loadresident" LINK Usage5} tool can be used to load
		resident tags to EXTRES buffer after running
		BlizKick. @{"protectextresbuf" LINK Usage8} can be used to MMU
		protect the EXTRES buffer memory.

		@{"Installation" LINK Installation} automagically defines BKMODPATH
		variable to "DEVS:Modules/".

		@{"applypatch" LINK Usage3} program can be used to "prepatch"
		ROM image.

  @{b}EXTRESBUF/N@{ub}
		Insufficient @{"free ROM space" LINK Planting} isn't a problem
		anymore! With this keyword you can specify
		amount of memory (in bytes) which is allocated
		for the external "module" buffer. Now you can
		plant any number of @{"modules" LINK Modules}!
		@{b}EXTRESBUF requires at least V36 ROM image!@{ub}

		See @{"How to calculate EXTRESBUF amount" LINK EXTRESBUFAmount}. Please
		note that there is no need to calculate exact
		value for EXTRESBUF, just use large enough buffer.
		Good values are 50000, 100000, 150000 and so on.

		@{b}NOTE:@{ub} If you use this feature then this
		kicked ROM @{b}mustn't@{ub} be ripped with SaveROM or any
		other similar program. This means: don't rip ROM
		Image from BlizKicked Amiga, if EXTRESBUF was
		used.

		@{"loadresident" LINK Usage5} tool can be used to
		load resident tags to EXTRES buffer after running
		BlizKick. @{"protectextresbuf" LINK Usage8} can be used to MMU
		protect the EXTRES buffer memory.

		@{b}NOTE:@{ub} ShowConfig output gets a bit @{"garbled" LINK ShowConfigBug}.

  @{b}SANITY/K/N@{ub}
		This argument specifies safery buffer size that
		is allocated after EXTRESBEF. If you seem to get
		weird crashes and/or alert 80010000 use
		SANITY=1000. If it still fails try ~2000 or ~4000.
		Note that using this option reduces the largest
		available memory block (ie. causes fragmentition).

		@{b}NOTE:@{ub} Normally this option is not needed.

  @{b}FORCE/S@{ub}
		If this switch is specified BlizKick will kick
		this ROM image, even if it has same version
		and revision number and checksum as in the
		currently kicked ROM. This is switch is also
		needed if you're about to use grabbed ROM that
		has been previously used with BlizKick. This
		switch comes in handy if you use scripts to
		lauch different Kickstart versions. With FORCE
		you can ensure that Kickstart really changes,
		even if you've used BlizKick previously.
		@{b}CAUTION!! DO NOT SPECIFY THIS SWITCH IF
		YOU USE BLIZKICK IN S:STARTUP-SEQUENCE
		OR YOU'LL GET @{"INFINITE BOOT LOOP" LINK Bootloop}.@{ub}

  @{b}(LOCALFAST/S)@{ub}
		By using this switch you can have memory on
		your Blizzard board used for RAD-disks and
		reset-proof programs. If there's enough memory
		provided you can have @{b}huge@{ub} RAD-disk!
		This also enables fast memory for exec.library
		and supervisor stack.

		@{u}This feature has been disabled in BlizKick 1.20+.
		As of BlizKick 1.21 you can use external module
		called @{"LocalFast" LINK Modules} instead.@{uu}

		Note that most new cards do @{b}NOT@{ub} need this
		module, only some old Blizzard 1230s.

		@{b}NOTE:@{ub} If you use LocalFast module you must
		start BlizKick before PoolMem.

  @{b}(QUICKBOOT/S)@{ub}
		If this switch is specified BlizKick will
		bypass flashy delay in Blizzard boards' boot.
		@{b}NOTE:@{ub} Bypassing can cause problems! My hard
		disk doesn't boot when I use this feature!
		Note also that this thing currently only
		works on Pre-IV 1230 boards.

		@{u}This feature has been disabled in BlizKick 1.20+.
		As of BlizKick 1.22 you can use external module
		called @{"QuickBoot" LINK Modules} instead.@{uu}

		@{b}NOTE:@{ub} If you use QuickBoot module you @{b}must@{ub}
		use LocalFast module too or else you're in trouble.

  @{b}SPEEDROM/S@{ub}
		This feature will speed up ROM. It will
		remove/disable some not so important parts of
		the ROM to gain some speed.

  @{b}HOGWAITBLIT/S@{ub}
		If you have an AGA chipset you use this switch
		to patch graphics.library/WaitBlit() to turn
		@{"BLITHOG" LINK BLITHOG} on during blit wait. This does almost
		the same thing as @{"FastWaitBlit" LINK FastWaitBlit} by Dave Jones,
		but is even @{"faster" LINK GfxBenchmarks}.
		HOGWAITBLIT requires V39 or better ROM image.

  @{b}CPUCARD/S@{ub}
		Specify this if you use CPU Card. Should work
		at least with CBM (A3640) and Cyberstorm MKI
		cards. Cyberstorm MKII, MKIII and PPC are
		detected automatically so don't use this switch
		with those.

		@{b}NOTE:@{ub} If you experience problems try placing
		BlizKick commandline after SetPatch -line.

  @{b}IGNPATH=IGNOREBKMODPATH/S@{ub}
		If this switch is present MODULE option load
		the modules relative to current directory. Also
		BKMODPATH environment variable is not used then.

  @{b}NOPUPREBOOT/S@{ub}
                Use the new reboot method with PowerUP boards,
                this try to avoid the infamous
                @{"RED screen crash at cold start" LINK TroubleShoot} problem.
		(Only affect PowerUP cards)

  @{b}KEEPEXEC/S@{ub}
		Try to retain exec.library and reset proof
                applications when rebooting the system. There
                really is no reason to use this switch, but
                sometimes it could be useful, if the reset
                proof application can cope ROM changing on
                them. @{b}PLEASE DON'T USE THIS SWITCH WITHOUT
                A GOOD REASON@{ub}. You have been warned. Normal
                users can forget all about this switch. :)

  @{b}QUIET/S@{ub}
		Guess what happens if you specify this switch?
		There won't be any output at all! =o)

Under 1.x Kickstart you cannot use MODULE, FORCE, SPEEDROM, HOGWAITBLIT or QUIET because the whole paramline is interpeted as KICKFILE name. Original Kickstart will be restored if you don't specify KICKFILE parameter. Also, you can't specify keyword KICKFILE in the argument line:

1.x		@{b}BlizKick DEVS:rom image 3.1@{ub}
2.04 +		@{b}BlizKick KICKFILE "DEVS:rom image 3.1"@{ub}


If you want to rekick for example Kickstart 1.3 then you need the ROM image itself (in @{"devs:rom1.3" LINK Kick13} file in this example). Write in CLI/Shell:

@{b}1.Workbench> BlizKick DEVS:rom1.3@{ub}

If everything worked ok system should boot up with KS 1.3.

If you want to start BlizKick automatically (you use never Kickstart than on your chip all the time, KS 3.1 on 3.0 machine, as in this example), you need to copy BlizKick executable into your C: -drawer (if not yet done) and insert the following line to the beginning of your s:startup-sequence file:

@{b}C:BlizKick DEVS:rom3.1 QUIET@{ub}

Now, at the first system boot up the new ROM image will be kicked. Your system will boot twice at power-up, but that isn't too disturbing, I think!

@{b}NOTE:@{ub} You @{b}should@{ub} install BlizKick @{b}before@{ub} any reset-proof programs because BlizKick will trash execbase. If you install it after any other reset-proof program you might get @{"infinite boot loop" LINK Bootloop}.

If multiple reset-proof patches are used you can have triple boot at power-up (Just a slow-down).

After rekicking system with BlizKick there is virtually nothing that can trash the new ROM (except accessing @{"certain" LINK doub!} very high memory addresses). Of course, power-down will restore the original ROM.

@{b}NOTE:@{ub} If you rekick older kickstart than originally used one, it may be impossible to use all hardware and/or peripherals of your system (e.g. If you originally use KS 3.x in your A1200 and rekick KS 1.3 you can't use your hard disk drives or PCMCIA slot. Direct banging of AGA hardware works, if someone is smart (?) enough to do it).

You can easily build cool system in which you can select kickstart by clicking cooresponding icon, you can use @{b}iconx@{ub} program and scripts.

See @{"usage" LINK Usage2} of the SaveROM program.

     @{b}ERROR CONDITIONS@{ub}

RC (return code) is set:

  OK (0)
		BlizKick installed ok. You'll never see this,
		though... :)
  WARN (5)
		BlizKick isn't needed. You're trying to kick
		same ROM image as currently used.
  ERROR (10)
		Things went wrong. Couldn't get memory?
		Couldn't access kickfile? Invalid ROM image?
		You're trying to restore kickstart, but you
		haven't used BlizKick to kick it previously?
		Failed to plant module?
  FAIL (20)
		Something fatal happened! Dos didn't open? No
		phase5/DCE turbo board or MAPROM jumper not
		installed?

Some special error codes can be generated by BlizKick in addition to standard error codes (see your AmigaDOS Users's Guide for expanation of most common errors.)
Problems concerning module system begin with line: "Couldn't plant module 'modulename'!"

205: "object not found"

  Module file can't be found.

207: "object too large"

  Module can't fit into ROM. Use EXTRESBUF, or if it's already in use @{"increase" LINK EXTRESBUFAmount} the amount of allocated memory.

212: "object is not of required type"

  Module file you specified is not valid.

118: "wrong number of arguments"

  You have specified multiple occurences of module that can only be planted once.

     @{b}EXAMPLES@{ub}

@{b}C:BlizKick DEVS:rom40068@{ub}
Now then... This line does nothing special, it only installs v40.68 ROM and reboots if it is not yet installed.

@{b}C:BlizKick@{ub}
This commandline restores original ROM if it was previously kicked with BlizKick.

@{b}c:BlizKick DEVS:rom40068.A1200.patched EXTRESBUF=90000 MODULE FusionReserve FixGetMsg AlertFix FileSystem.resource FastFileSystem scsi.device ram-handler console.device SpeedyIDE QUIET@{ub}
This is the first line in my s:startup-sequence. It uses @{"applypatched" LINK Usage3} (SPEEDROM NoClick FixMath404 SpeedyIDE PatchMath020 romfixes) v40.68 ROM Image (A1200), 90000 byte EXTRES buffer, and uses FusionReserve, AlertFix, FileSystem.resource, FastFileSystem, scsi.device, ram-handler, console.device and SpeedyIDE modules, disabling annoying drive clicking, fixing 68060 GetMsg() loop hang, fixing bug from V40.4 mathieeesingbas.library, optimizing some math routines inside ROM, fixing some @{"rom bugs" LINK rombugs}, allowing me to get rid of ShapeShifter's PrepareEmul (and Fusion's rsrvcold/warm), fixing Blizzard PPC @{"crash + reboot + alert" LINK blizzppcfeatures} problem, installing @{"AmigaOS 3.5" LINK OS35setup} filesystem.resource, fastfilesystem, scsi.device, ram-handler and console.device and speeding up scsi.device access.

@{b}C:BlizKick DEVS:rom40068.A1200 EXTRESBUF=16384 HOGWAITBLIT SPEEDROM MODULE NoClick FixMath404 PrepareEmul BBlank SCSIDEV43 SpeedyIDE RemCards QUIET@{ub}
This was the first line in my s:startup-sequence when I had B1230-III. It uses v40.68 ROM Image (A1200), 16K EXTRES buffer, speeds up gfx WaitBlit, speeds up ROM, and uses NoClick, FixMath404, PrepareEmul, BBlank, SCSIDEV43, SpeedyIDE and RemCards modules, disabling annoying drive clicking, fixing bug from V40.4 mathieeesingbas.library, allowing me to get rid of ShapeShifter's PrepareEmul, enabling borderblanking already in bootmenu, installing beta V43 scsi.device, speeding scsi.device access and removing all PCMCIA stuff from system. Phew! Nice one, ehh? ;)

@{b}C:BlizKick DEVS:rom40068.A1200 EXTRESBUF=32768 HOGWAITBLIT SPEEDROM MODULE NoClick FixMath404 PrepareEmul BBlank SoftSCSI SCSIDEV43 SpeedyIDE RemCards QUIET@{ub}
If I'd have B1260, I'd probably use this commandline. SoftSCSI module "replaces" SCSI (ep)rom (27C256) of BLIZZARD 1230-IV, 1240-T/ERC or 1260, allowing use of latest SCSI driver beta ROM with SCSI-Kit.

@{b}C:BlizKick DEVS:rom40068.A1200 EXTRESBUF=512 MODULE DEVS:Modules/FixMath404 QUIET@{ub}
This line will only fix bug from V40.4 mathieeesingbas.library.

@{b}C:BlizKick DEVS:rom37300@{ub}
Anyone wants to test software on kick 2.05? ;) BTW: PCMCIA slot and hard drives work with ROM 37.300!!

@{b}C:BlizKick DEVS:rom34005@{ub}
Will give you a handy pic... saying KS 1.3. @{b}NOTE:@{ub} works on most 060 systems too!

@{b}C:BlizKick * EXTRESBUF=256 HOGWAITBLIT@{ub}
This line will use the original ROM found in chip and use HOGWAITBLIT.

@{b}C:BlizKick * EXTRESBUF 256 HOGWAITBLIT DEVS:Modules/MoveVBR@{ub}
This line will use the original ROM found in chip and use HOGWAITBLIT, plus move VBR to fast memory.

     @{b}WHAT BLIZKICK COMMANDLINE SHOULD I USE?@{ub}

Okay. Now this is the tricky part: you need to experiment and find out what modules you need/want. It hardly makes sense to add every module there is. This will not work. Read @{"description of the modules" LINK Modules} carefully and try to figure out what you need. Some modules require specific hardware or software, so spend few minutes on this.. :) BlizKick never was or will be easy to use, I didn't claim that. If you really can't work out configuration for your system, ask your local amiga guru or take my configuration and remove the stuff that doesn't work on your system.

@ENDNODE
@NODE ShowConfigBug "Garbled ShowConfig output"
4·Workbench:% showconfig
PROCESSOR:      CPU 68060/68060fpu/68060mmu
CUSTOM CHIPS:   AA PAL Alice (id=$0023), AA Lisa (id=$00F8)
VERS:   Kickstart version 40.68, Exec version 40.10, Disk version 44.2
RAM:    Node type $A, Attributes $405 (FAST), at $7672AD78-$79EFFFFF (57216 K)
        Node type $A, Attributes $415 (FAST), at $76000000-$7672AD77 (7360 K)
        Node type $A, Attributes $703 (CHIP), at $760002F0-$1FFFFF (@{b}~2210.0 meg@{ub})
BOARDS:
 Board + ROM (HD?) (phase 5):   Prod=8512/110($2140/$6E) (@$F00C38 128K)
@ENDNODE
@NODE EXTRESBUFAmount "Calculating EXTRESBUF amount"

     @{b}CALCULATING EXTRESBUF AMOUNT@{ub}

@{"EXTRESBUF" LINK Usage1} argument of BlizKick can be used to increase @{"free ROM space" LINK Planting} when external @{"Modules" LINK Modules} are installed.

The value given for EXTRESBUF depends of selected modules and @{"ROM Image version" LINK Planting}. In most cases 40960 bytes is sufficient.

To understand memory requirements of modules you should know that there are (currently) two types of them: "real" and "patch" modules. "real" modules need some space for themselves, but "patch" ones need not.

Here are approximated memory requirements for currently included modules:

    A1000Jingle		 ~8 Kbytes
    AlertFix		362 bytes
    BBlank		 88 bytes
    BPPCFix		152 bytes
    BPPCFix11		144 bytes
    BPPCFix040		192 bytes
    ChipSaver		272 bytes
    Colour		240 bytes
    FusionReserve	208 bytes
    LocalFast		136 bytes
    MoveVBR		160 bytes
    NewAlert		824 bytes
    QuickBoot		136 bytes
    Replace		344 bytes
    RebootFix		72 bytes
    SCSIDEV43		~13 Kbytes
    SpeedyChip		384 bytes
    SoftSCSI		138 bytes + ~20Kbytes (A1234.ROM)
    Test		264 bytes

Other modules included in BlizKick package are plain "patch" type, so they don't need any ROM space.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Planting "Plainting 'Modules'"

     @{b}PLANTING MODULES@{ub}

There's some empty space in 512K ROM images. This space can be used for BlizKick's "@{"modules" LINK Modules}", allowing bug fixes, patches, speed-up kludges etc.

Size of the free space area varies between different Kickstart releases, here is some information:

@{b}Kickstart		Empty space in bytes@{ub}

37.175			2276 + 10216
37.300			132 + 24
39.106			404 + 100
40.63			32 + 452
40.68			84 ;-(
40.70			4800 + 4

Now you're no more limited by "empty space"! You can expand the module buffer by using @{"EXTRESBUF" LINK Usage1} feature!
@ENDNODE
@NODE Modules "About BlizKick 'Modules'"

     @{b}BLIZKICK MODULES@{ub}

With BlizKick "Modules" you can expand the current Kickstart ROM.

There are currently @{"thirty-two" LINK ExampleModules} example modules included, but I expect @{b}you@{ub} to code more...

See @{"module programming examples" LINK ExampleModules}.

P.S. If someone is in need for some features in BlizKick they can (mostly) be easily implemented with external modules. I suppose Aminet will be full of PD/Freeware BlizKick modules soon... ;-) I made this possible because I @{b}can and will not@{ub} change BlizKick constantly...

So if you think something essential is missing, look Aminet first, then ask your programming skilled friend to do it, and finally, if nothing else helps: contact @{"me" LINK About}.

     @{b}INCLUDED BLIZKICK MODULES@{ub}

@{u}A1000Jingle@{uu} playing A1000 boottune.

@{u}AlertFix@{uu} fixes Blizzard PPC @{"`crash + reboot + alert' problem" LINK blizzppcfeatures} and other Alert bugs. NOTE: If you use both NewAlert and AlertFix you're recommended to specify NewAlert before AlertFix.

@{u}BBlank@{uu} turns on borderblank, even in bootmenu.

@{u}BPPCFix(11)@{uu} and @{u}BPPCFix040@{uu} subtitute BPPCFix by Frank Wille <frank@phoenix.owl.de>. BPPCFix module disables the flashrom ppc.library of BlizzarzPPC board. BPPCFix040 module disables 68040.library (and 68060.library if available). If you want to disable both ppc.library and 0x0 libraries use both modules. BPPCFix11 is the older 1.1 version of the BPPCFix module. You can use that if the new module doesn't work.

@{u}ChipSaver@{uu} is *the ultimate* ripping aid! When installed this module will copy *whole* chip memory to fastmem if right mouse button is pressed while booting thus enabling to rip any music module. This module creates so-called $100 -buffer which can be used with most advanced module rippers (ExoticRipper for example). Included tool, Free100buf, can be used to free this buffer if you want to get rid of it. For technical reasons you should have at least four (4) megabytes of memory installed on your BLIZZARD turbo board (hackish code inside TM). This shouldn't be a problem nowadays though... :) Note also that reset surviving programs (RAD etc.) should not be used when using ChipSaver. Don't use this module in everyday use!

@{u}Colour@{uu} displays some dull colour bars on screen. Useless really.

@{u}FixGetMsg@{uu} fixes hang that happens on 68060 system if program calls GetMsg() in tight loop. Substitutes FixGetMsg by Frederick H. G. Wright II <fw@well.com>.

@{u}FixMath404@{uu} fixes two bugs in V40.4 mathieeesingbas.library (non-FPU IEEESPMul() and IEEESPDiv() are disconnected). Note that A3000 ROMs don't need this module (its mathieeesingbas.library does only have FPU routines, since A3000 is guaranteed to have a FPU).

@{u}FusionReserve@{uu} substitutes FUSION's RsrvCold tool (Also Mac1200). Also substitutes ShapeShifter's PrepareEmul tool.

@{u}hackdisk@{uu} replaces trackdisk.device with faster and more reliable code. Useless if want to use @{"v6/v7 CrossDos" LINK TroubleShoot}.

@{u}LocalFast@{uu} does the same as pre-1.20 BlizKick @{"LOCALFAST option" LINK Usage1}, this is to move exec.library and supervisor stack to fastmemory. Also makes RAD: use fastmem instead of chipmem. @{b}NOTE1: Only use this module if you need to (mainly Blizzard 12x0s)! NOTE2: If you use LocalFast module you must start BlizKick before PoolMem.@{ub}

@{u}Magia@{uu} is a funny example on how to replace strings in rom (Amiga -> Magia). Useless really.

@{u}MoveVBR@{uu} moves low level interrupt vector table to fastmem. Note that also FusionReserve module moves VBR to fastmem.

@{u}MuMove4K@{uu} prepares system memory for MuFastZero's FastExec option. Substitutes MuMove4K by Thomas Richter.

@{u}NewAlert@{uu} is improved alert.hook, displaying task/process name. NOTE: If you use both NewAlert and AlertFix you're recommended to specify NewAlert before AlertFix.

@{u}NoClick@{uu} turns off drive clicking. Supports hackdisk module.

@{u}PatchMath020@{uu} optimizes C-compiler math routines inside ROM.

@{u}PrepareEmul@{uu} substitutes ShapeShifter's PrepareEmul tool. Note that FusionReserve module works with both FUSION and ShapeShifter, so you probably should use that.

@{u}QuickBoot@{uu} does the same as pre-1.20 BlizKick @{"QUICKBOOT option" LINK Usage1}, this is to disable board initcode completely (ie. the flashy display on Blizzard cards). @{b}NOTE1: This module can cause boot problems, ie. you might not be able to boot from hard disk! NOTE2: You MUST use LocalFast module too if you use this!@{ub}

@{u}ramlibstack@{uu} fixes ramlib stack to 8k instead of original 2k. Substitutes MCPRamlibPatch. Also romfixes module has this functionality! Adding both romfixes and ramlibstack causes an error!

@{u}RebootFix@{uu} module fixes reboot problems with A1200 and 060 (at least BLIZZARD 1260) when display is in multisync mode. This module is hacky so please don't use it unless you really need it.

@{u}RemCards@{uu} patch disables all PCMCIA stuff from system, thus freeing some memory and system resources.

@{u}Replace@{uu} is a example on how to replace existing rom parts. Useless really (just an programming exaple).

@{u}romfixes@{uu} fixing some @{"rom bugs" LINK rombugs}. This module is a @{b}must@{ub}!

@{u}SCSIDEV43@{uu} patches Kickstart 3.0 or newer to use beta V43 scsi.device. No more @{"4GB drive limit" LINK 4GBLimit}! Note that you need V43 scsi.device in DEVS:scsi43.device -file. The beta scsi.device can be obtained from SCSI_IDE43_nn developer package, "a300.ld_strip" is to be used with A1200, "a1000.ld_strip" with A4000[T] IDE, "a4000t.ld_strip" with A4000T SCSI and "scsidisk.ld_strip" with A3000[T]. You must move correct file (according to your system configuration) to DEVS:scsi43.device -file. This module is obsolete (if using non-beta scsi.device!), you can use correct .ld_strip file as module directly!

@{u}SoftSCSI@{uu} replaces the SCSI ROM of BLIZZARD 1230-IV, 1240-T/ERC or 1260 via software. Requires A1234.ROM file in DEVS:Modules directory! Substitutes SoftSCSI program by Gideon Zenz.

@{u}SpeedyChip@{uu} module patches 060 MMU lists improving chip memory write speed! 68060 only. NOTE: This module is obsolete with phase5/DCE 68060.library V46+.

@{u}SpeedyIDE@{uu} patch speeds up IDE-devices accessed with scsi.device upto 20%! (or even more! yes, this does work!) New IDEFix97 software has this functionality built-in.

@{u}Test@{uu} is a simple example on how to add a library to rom. Useless really (just an programming exaple).

@{u}WaitIDE@{uu} patches Kickstart 3.0 or newer to wait all IDE devices (even those slowly spinning-up ones!).


See @{"How to calculate EXTRESBUF amount" LINK EXTRESBUFAmount}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE 4GBLimit "SCSIDEV43 -- Get beyond 4GB limit!"

     @{b}NOTES ABOUT >4GB DEVICES@{ub}

SCSIDEV43 module can be used to kick Kickstart ROM to use 64bit V43 scsi.device which supports over-4GB drives. There are some caveats though:

1. You must also use V43 FFS in RDB to make use of V43 scsi.device. Without this new filesystem over-4GB cannot be accessed correctly (new FastFileSystem can be obtained from FFS43_nn developer package).

2. Because BlizKick is loaded from disk, the partition on which BlizKick and related files are located should not exceed 4GB size. It might work, but probably not. You should not use over-4GB drives as boot disks, that is. The sefest way would be to mount such partitions manually in DEVS:DosDrivers/ or in S:startup-sequence.

You might also want to use DirectSCSI version of AFS/pfs2/pfs3 or SFS instead.
@ENDNODE
@NODE AminetModules "BlizKick Module Names (in Aminet)"

     @{b}MODULE NAMING CONVENTIONS@{ub}

Q: What should I call my module?
A: Name should tell what the module does or be otherwise descriptive. For example: I've used such names as PrepareEmul and SoftSCSI when my module replaces these programs. I also think that 'NoClick' and 'hackdisk' are kind of descriptive names. Hint: Think about module name before uploading... Could it be even better?

Q: So now I have created my own module... Where and with what name should I put it into Aminet then?
A: The first BlizKick module pioneer Christian Sauer <sauer@cip.informatik.uni-wuerzburg.de> created the standard... ;) So I'll advice you to do it in same way:

1. Name the lha packaga as BK_<modulename>.lha.
2. Put your lha package to util/boot directory in Aminet. (Type:  util/boot)

     EXAMPLE (util/boot/BK_FooHelloWorld.lha)

Short:    BlizKick-Module: Says "hello world" while booting
Author:   foojack@inter.net (Jack the Coder)
Uploader: foojack@inter.net (Jack the Coder)
Type:     util/boot

FooHelloWorld is a module for BlizKick by Harry Sintonen. It says
"Hello World" while system is booting... etc... blahblah...
@ENDNODE
@NODE ExampleModules "Programming modules"

     @{b}PROGRAMMING MODULES@{ub}

Programming BlizKick modules is relatively easy. If you've ever written ResidentTag or a library/device you should be able to code a module.

Currently there are two different forms of BlizKick modules: @{b}"real"@{ub} modules and @{b}patch@{ub} modules.

There are numerous example sources included (source codes for all included modules in fact:):

  @{b}file			type description@{ub}

  @{"A1000Jingle.ASM" LINK Modules/A1000Jingle.ASM/main}	 m   Plays A1000 bootjingle
  @{"AlertFix.ASM" LINK Modules/AlertFix.ASM/main}		 p   Complex rom patch to fix alerts
  @{"BBlank.ASM" LINK Modules/BBlank.ASM/main}		 m   Turn on border blanking
  @{"BPPCFix.ASM" LINK Modules/BPPCFix.ASM/main}		 m   Disable BPPC ppc.library
  @{"BPPCFix11.ASM" LINK Modules/BPPCFix11.ASM/main}		 m   Disable BPPC ppc.library (V1.1)
  @{"BPPCFix040.ASM" LINK Modules/BPPCFix040.ASM/main}	 m   Disable BPPC 040/060.library
  @{"ChipSaver.ASM" LINK Modules/ChipSaver.ASM/main}		 p   Copy chip to fastmem if RMB
  @{"Colour.ASM" LINK Modules/Colour.ASM/main}		 m   Colour-bars on screen
  @{"FixGetMsg.ASM" LINK Modules/FixGetMsg.ASM/main}		 m   Fixes GetMsg() loop hang on 68060
  @{"FixMath404.ASM" LINK Modules/FixMath404.ASM/main}	 p   Fixes mathieeesingbas.library 40.4
  @{"FusionReserve.ASM" LINK Modules/FusionReserve.ASM/main}	 p   Substitutes RsrvCold
  @{"hackdisk.ASM" LINK Modules/hackdisk.ASM/main}		 p   Makes hackdisk.dev resident
  @{"LocalFast.ASM" LINK Modules/LocalFast.ASM/main}		 p   exec & sv stack to fast
  @{"Magia.ASM" LINK Modules/Magia.ASM/main}		 p   Changes ROM strings :)
  @{"MoveVBR.ASM" LINK Modules/MoveVBR.ASM/main}		 m   Moves VBR to fastmem
  @{"MuMove4K.ASM" LINK Modules/MuMove4K.ASM/main}		 m   Prepare lowmem for MuFastZero.
  @{"NewAlert.ASM" LINK Modules/NewAlert.ASM/main}		 m   Improved alert.hook
  @{"NoClick.ASM" LINK Modules/NoClick.ASM/main}		 p   Turns off drive clicking
  @{"PatchMath020.ASM" LINK Modules/PatchMath020.ASM/main}	 p   020+ Optimizes ROM image
  @{"PrepareEmul.ASM" LINK Modules/PrepareEmul.ASM/main}	 p   Moves chipmem start to $2000
  @{"ramlibstack.ASM" LINK Modules/ramlibstack.ASM/main}	 p   Fix ramlib stack to 8k
  @{"QuickBoot.ASM" LINK Modules/QuickBoot.ASM/main}		 p   Disable flashy blizzard bootdelay
  @{"RebootFix.ASM" LINK Modules/RebootFix.ASM/main}		 m   Fix A1200/060 reboot
  @{"RemCards.ASM" LINK Modules/RemCards.ASM/main}		 p   Removes PCMCIA stuff
  @{"Replace.ASM" LINK Modules/Replace.ASM/main}		 m   Replaces OS "alert.hook"
  @{"romfixes.ASM" LINK Modules/romfixes.ASM/main}		 p   Fixes some rom bugs
  @{"SCSIDEV43.ASM" LINK Modules/SCSIDEV43.ASM/main}		 p   Kick V43 beta scsi.device
  @{"SoftSCSI.ASM" LINK Modules/SoftSCSI.ASM/main}		 m   Installs SCSI ROM kicktag
  @{"SpeedyChip.ASM" LINK Modules/SpeedyChip.ASM/main}	 m   Speed up 060 chipmem writes
  @{"SpeedyIDE.ASM" LINK Modules/SpeedyIDE.ASM/main}		 p   Speed up IDE upto 20%
  @{"Test.ASM" LINK Modules/Test.ASM/main}		 m   "testmodule.library"
  @{"WaitIDE.ASM" LINK Modules/WaitIDE.ASM/main}		 p   Wait IDE spin-up

You should also peek @{"blizkickmodule.i" LINK Modules/blizkickmodule.i/main}.

If you're about to release your BlizKick module in Aminet, see @{"module naming conventions" LINK AminetModules}.

You can, of course, distribute your modules and patches in any form you like [#?ware (or *ware if you're UN*X fan :-)].
@ENDNODE
@NODE BLITHOG "Blitter BLITHOG mode"

     @{b}BLITHOG MODE@{ub}

The BLITHOG ("blitter-nasty") bit controls the blitter DMA priority (over CPU micro). If BLITHOG is on it'll prevent CPU from stealing any bus cycles while blitter DMA is running.

Normally BLITHOG is off.
@ENDNODE
@NODE GfxBenchmarks "Graphics Benchmarks"

     @{b}GRAPHICS BENCHMARKS@{ub}

Hardware: Amiga 1200, BLIZZARD 1230-III, 16MB 60ns SIMM,
	   Kickstart 3.1 (V40.68)
Software: SetPatch 43.5, AIBB 6.5

ROM	- @{"MAPROM" LINK MAPROMJumper} off
MROM	- MAPROM on
FWB	- @{"FastWaitBlit 2.12" LINK FastWaitBlit}, MAPROM on
BHOG	- @{"BLITHOG" LINK BLITHOG} and MAPROM on
HWB	- BlizKick @{"HOGWAITBLIT" LINK Usage1}, MAPROM on

		@{b}ROM	MROM	FWB	BHOG	HWB@{ub}

WritePixel	7345	10674	10552	10776	@{b}10674@{ub}
EllipseTest	7.96	6.77	6.83	6.83	@{b}6.70@{ub}
TGTest		1420	1680	1678	1698	@{b}1729@{ub}
LineTest	1385	1431	1431	1432	@{b}1445@{ub}

WritePixel	- Pixels/Second
EllipseTest	- Seconds
TGTest		- Characters/Second
LineTest	- Lines/Second

As we can see BlizKick's HOGWAITBLIT gives the best results. HOGWAITBLIT is faster than FastWaitBlit because BlizKick automagically ;-) patches also Kickstart ROM's internal calls to WaitBlit().

HOGWAITBLIT is average 1.64 % faster than ROM code (MAPROM on).

HOGWAITBLIT is average 1.78 % faster than @{"FastWaitBlit 2.12" LINK FastWaitBlit}.

NOTES:
a) MAPROM off results are with KS 3.0 and 8MB 70ns SIMM.
@ENDNODE
@NODE FastWaitBlit "FastWaitBlit program"

     @{b}FASTWAITBLIT@{ub}

FastWaitBlit 2.12, GiftWare, Aminet
Author: Dave Jones <DJones@CardiffCyberCafe.Co.Uk>

FastWaitBlit program turns @{"BLITHOG" LINK BLITHOG} on while system is waiting for blit to finish. This will speed up graphics, at the cost of CPU performance.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Usage2 "How do I use SaveROM?"

     @{b}USAGE@{ub}

SameROM's usage is

  SaveROM @{b}<KICKFILE>@{ub}

  @{b}<KICKFILE>@{ub}
                Here you specify full path for the ROM image
		to save. You can't quate the filename, even
		if it contains spaces!
		e.g. SaveROM DEVS:rom image 1.3

SaveROM functions identically in all Kickstart versions: The whole paramline is interpeted as KICKFILE name.

RC (return code) is set:

  OK (0)
		SaveROM succeeded.
  ERROR (10)
		Couldn't create or write kickfile! Destination
		file is removed.
  FAIL (20)
		Something fatal happened! Dos didn't open?


Here is a detailed example of the SaveROM use: @{"Get Kickstart 1.3 ROM" LINK Kick13}.
@ENDNODE
@NODE Bootloop "Infinite boot loop"

     @{b}BOOT LOOP@{ub}

If you don't install BlizKick as your first reset-proof program you might get infinite boot loop. This happens because BlizKick trashes execbase and therefore any reset-proof programs run before BlizKick will get flushed from memory. If you experience such a problem just press both mouse buttons while your Amiga is booting and you'll get to bootmenu. Then select 'Boot without Startup-sequence' -button. Now you must edit your s:startup-sequence file: move BlizKick as your first reset-proof program or if BlizKick refuses to work properly, remove it completely (and report the problem to @{"me" LINK About}).

If you use FORCE switch in your startup-sequence, you @{b}will@{ub} get infinite boot loop, @{b}so don't use it there!@{ub}
@ENDNODE
